    "gp_section_566798216319075265": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "cde66273dbb0533a0f994219018a20f65db2a9d772fdeae2ccb8c4ff8d5b9566_1_1_0_0__1",
        "gg4YoJ0BCta_text": "<p>But as we get older or spend more time sitting, <strong>those muscles weaken</strong>. When your calves don’t contract properly, blood and fluid can get stuck in your lower legs, l<strong>eading to swelling</strong>, poor circulation, and <strong>pain</strong> that builds up over time.</p>",
        "ggBW_fUjV_n_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0252/1261/6781/files/gempages_464015397612422087-b200e162-575f-48fa-bd7e-0d53cc4cbf66.png",
        "ggGkzemG1js_text": "<span style=\"color:#055BDC;\"><strong>Feel lighter, stronger, and pain-free - your freedom to move starts here.</strong></span>",
        "ggQAm8x-ujQ_text": "<p>That’s why pills, creams, and even compression socks rarely give lasting relief - they don’t address the root cause. To truly feel better, <strong>you need to restore healthy blood flow</strong> by gently activating your calves - just like walking does, without the strain.</p>",
        "ggWQIG9fsLw_text": "The Real Reason Your Legs Feel Heavy, Swollen, and Stiff",
        "ggj3LHKR5Jp_text": "<p>If your legs and feet feel heavy, swollen, or sore by the end of the day, the real issue may not be your feet at all - <strong>it’s your calves</strong>. Doctors often call them your <strong>“second heart”</strong> because they help pump blood from your lower body back to your heart.</p>",
        "ggymlr3ksYA_text": "The Real Reason Your Legs Feel Heavy, Swollen, and Stiff"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-566798216319075265"
    },
